What is causing this issue and how can I fix it? I believe it may be trying to update descriptorsets while they are still in use.
assistant: The error indicates that you are trying to update a descriptor set that is currently in use by a command buffer which is in the pending state. To fix this issue, you can wait until the command buffer has finished executing or you can use more descriptor sets and update the next available one, rather than updating the currently bound one.

One possible approach is to allocate multiple descriptor sets for each object in the scene and only update the descriptor set that is not in use by pending command buffers. You can use a simple descriptor set pool or manager that allocates a descriptor set when needed and manages a set of free or available descriptor sets.

Here is a basic example of how you can implement this:

1. Create a DescriptorSetPool class that handles the allocation and management of descriptor sets:

```cpp
class DescriptorSetPool
{
public:
    void Initialize(VkDescriptorPool pool, VkDescriptorSetLayout layout);
    VkDescriptorSet Allocate();
    void Free(VkDescriptorSet set);
    // Add functions to deallocate resources if necessary

private:
    std::vector<VkDescriptorSet> freeDescriptorSets;
    VkDescriptorPool descriptorPool;
    VkDescriptorSetLayout descriptorSetLayout;
};
```

2. Implement the allocation and freeing of descriptor sets in DescriptorSetPool:

```cpp
void DescriptorSetPool::Initialize(VkDescriptorPool pool, VkDescriptorSetLayout layout)
{
    descriptorPool = pool;
    descriptorSetLayout = layout;
}

VkDescriptorSet DescriptorSetPool::Allocate()
{
    VkDescriptorSet set;
    if (freeDescriptorSets.empty())
    {
        VkDescriptorSetAllocateInfo allocInfo{};
        allocInfo.sType = VK_STRUCTURE_TYPE_DESCRIPTOR_SET_ALLOCATE_INFO;
        allocInfo.descriptorPool = descriptorPool;
        allocInfo.descriptorSetCount = 1;
        allocInfo.pSetLayouts = &descriptorSetLayout;

        if (vkAllocateDescriptorSets(device, &allocInfo, &set) != VK_SUCCESS)
        {
            throw std::runtime_error("Failed to allocate descriptor sets!");
        }
    }
    else
    {
        set = freeDescriptorSets.back();
        freeDescriptorSets.pop_back();
    }
    return set;
}

void DescriptorSetPool::Free(VkDescriptorSet set)
{
    freeDescriptorSets.push_back(set);
}
```

3. In your Renderer class, create a descriptor set pool object, `DescriptorSetPool descriptorSetPool;`.

4. Initialize the descriptor set pool after creating the descriptor pool and descriptor set layout in Renderer::Initialize:

```cpp
descriptorSetPool.Initialize(descriptorPool, descriptorSetLayout);
```

5. Instead of using the descriptor set directly from the material in the GameObject::Render function, allocate a descriptor set from the pool:

```cpp
VkDescriptorSet descriptorSet = descriptorSetPool.Allocate();
material->UpdateBufferBinding(descriptorSet, mvpBuffer, device, sizeof(MVP));
```

6. After the command buffer is finished executing (e.g., in Renderer::Present, after `vkQueuePresentKHR`), free the descriptor sets that were used in the previous frame:

```cpp
for (VkDescriptorSet set : usedDescriptorSets) {
    descriptorSetPool.Free(set);
}
usedDescriptorSets.clear();

// NOTE: Make sure you have a std::vector<VkDescriptorSet> usedDescriptorSets; in your Renderer class
```

7. In the GameObject::Render function, add the used descriptor set to the usedDescriptorSets vector:

```cpp
usedDescriptorSets.push_back(descriptorSet);
```

With this approach, you should have a flexible descriptor set pool that helps avoid updating descriptor sets which are in use by pending command buffers.

Keep in mind that this is a simple example that can be further optimized to suit your specific use case, you can implement smarter allocation management or reuse descriptor sets whenever possible.

