user: Write a C program ncpmvdir that copies or moves an entire directory tree rooted at a specific path in the home directory to a specific destination folder in the home directory minus the file types specified in the extension list.

Synopsis :
ncpmvdir [ source_dir] [destination_dir] [options] <extension list>

 Both source_dir and destination_dir can be either absolute or relative paths but must belong to the home directory hierarchy.
If the destination_dir is not present in the home directory hierarchy, it should be newly created.

options
  -cp copy the directory rooted at source_dir to destination_dir and do not delete
the directory (and contents) rooted at source_dir
 -mv move the directory rooted at source_dir to destination_dir and delete the
directory (and contents) rooted at source_dir

extension list: up to 6 file extensions can provided ( c , pdf, txt etc.)

If the extension list is provided with -cp:

The entire sub-tree rooted at source_dir along with all its folders/sub- folders/files (minus the file types listed in the extension list) must be copied onto the destination_dir.

All the folders/sub-folders/files must be copied onto destination_dir as per the original hierarchy at source_dir.

   If desintation_dir does not exist, it must be created. 

   If the extension list is provided with -mv:

The entire sub-tree rooted at source_dir along with all its folders/sub- folders/files (minus the file types listed in the extension list) must be moved onto the destination_dir.

All the folders/sub-folders/files must be moved onto destination_dir as per the original hierarchy at source_dir.

 If desintation_dir does not exist, it must be created.

 The original subtree rooted at source_dir must be deleted entirely along with its folders/sub-folders/files etc.

If the extension list is not provided, all files and folders must be copied or moved as per the option chosen.

Sample Runs
$ ncpmvdir ./folder1 ./folder2/folder3 -cp txt pdf
   This will copy the directory tree rooted at ./folder1 to ./folder2/folder3 as per
the source_dir hierarchy and will not copy the .txt and .pdf files 

$ ncpmvdir ~/folder1 ~/folder3 -mv
 This will move the entire directory tree rooted at ~/folder1 to ~/folder 3 along with all the files and folders as per the source_dir hierarchy
If the source directory does not exist or does not belong to the home directory hierarchy, an appropriate error message must be displayed.

Requirement:
You must use the system call nftw() that allows you to traverse a file tree. This system call
will recursively visit all the files/directories present in the tree and will call you own function (a function that you pass as a parameter).


Comments and explanation of the program
 You are required to include adequate and appropriate comments to explain the working of the program.

write the program as if an intermediate programmer is writing it and create different functions for activitires, the code should create a destination directory if not present and while copying and moving files it should follow the parent directory hierarchy from root to leaf
assistant: ```c
#include <errno.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <ftw.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <sys/stat.h>
#include <unistd.h>

#define MAX_EXTENSIONS 6
#define NOPENFD 15

typedef enum { COPY, MOVE } operation;

char *source_dir = NULL;
char *destination_dir = NULL;
operation op = COPY; // default operation is copy
char *extensions[MAX_EXTENSIONS];
int num_ext = 0;

void usage() {
  printf("Synopsis:\n");
  printf("ncpmvdir [source_dir] [destination_dir] [options] <extension list>\n");
  printf("Options:\n");
  printf("  -cp: copy the directory\n");
  printf("  -mv: move the directory\n");
  printf("Extension list: up to 6 file extensions can be provided\n");
  exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
}

void parse_args(int argc, char **argv) {
  if (argc < 3)
    usage();

  source_dir = argv[1];
  destination_dir = argv[2];

  for (int i = 3; i < argc; ++i) {
    if (strcmp(argv[i], "-cp") == 0)
      op = COPY;
    else if (strcmp(argv[i], "-mv") == 0)
      op = MOVE;
    else {
      if (num_ext >= MAX_EXTENSIONS) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Too many extensions!\n");
        usage();
      }
      extensions[num_ext++] = argv[i];
    }
  }
}

int has_extension(const char *path) {
  size_t path_len = strlen(path);
  for (int i = 0; i < num_ext; ++i) {
    size_t ext_len = strlen(extensions[i]);
    if (path_len >= ext_len && strcmp(path + path_len - ext_len, extensions[i]) == 0)
      return 1;
  }
  return 0;
}

int process_entry(const char *fpath, const struct stat *sb, int tflag, struct FTW *ftwbuf) {
  if (has_extension(fpath))
    return 0;

  int path_len = strlen(destination_dir) + 1 + strlen(fpath);
  char new_path[path_len];
  snprintf(new_path, path_len, "%s/%s", destination_dir, fpath);

  if (tflag == FTW_D) {
    mkdir(new_path, sb->st_mode); // might already exist if we're moving
  } else if (tflag == FTW_F) {
    int src_fd = open(fpath, O_RDONLY);
    int dest_fd = open(new_path, O_WRONLY | O_CREAT, sb->st_mode);
    if (src_fd == -1 || dest_fd == -1) {
      perror("open");
      return -1;
    }

    char buf[1024];
    ssize_t n;
    while ((n = read(src_fd, buf, sizeof(buf))) > 0)
      if (write(dest_fd, buf, n) != n) {
        perror("write");
        return -1;
      }

    if (n == -1) {
      perror("read");
      return -1;
    }

    if (close(src_fd) == -1 || close(dest_fd) == -1) {
      perror("close");
      return -1;
    }

    if (op == MOVE)
      if (unlink(fpath) == -1) {
        perror("unlink");
        return -1;
      }
  }

  return 0;
}

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
  parse_args(argc, argv);

  if (nftw(source_dir, &process_entry, NOPENFD, FTW_PHYS) == -1) {
    perror("nftw");
    exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
  }

  if (op == MOVE)
    if (rmdir(source_dir) == -1) {
      perror("rmdir");
      exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

  return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```
This program uses the `nftw()` system call to traverse a directory tree rooted at the source directory. The function `process_entry()` is called for each file and directory in the tree.

When `-cp` flag is used, the directory tree is copied to the destination directory, excluding files with extensions listed in the extension list. When `-mv` flag is used, the directory tree is moved to the destination directory, excluding files with extensions listed in the extension list. In this case, the original subtree rooted at the source directory is deleted after moving it to the destination directory.

Only a limited number of file operations are allowed, which can be set by defining `NOPENFD`. If the maximum limit is reached, the program may fail to copy or move the directory tree.

The command-line parsing function `parse_args()` handles the given input arguments and sets the global variables accordingly.
